://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/RTfNiIGh_WaVZMOsfR4Yt7eyGbbCb6403pkarR2TjylbttkXeFtx8i0rV6x__9DeztlZYgQxsgdoTCUmhYm3wG147xKaIdUrPHUZfsona00g3ytuIB6vPt0W3YCCEBTeXvzo4Wk0b9zgMnAxUZhSvIXYyJws2rpWW7sqAUnNimb15IVAi2rmCR9SUICiU10FgLFszqHPsApjcCJxLTI8lu53HFAd6IYekAyJ7bZNW-kT4jEhDoHzpwj19ugq9jqyYw_zEMheO1yz1ixay4I4EU6aSX--0KifyBAVI0dys3OLXFkwCHOx0u1JvYJdQbcn3sOCW8bFpJeWiyvISL5DecAqXxRP1fH74ECKrXmZbkxxi-wzKBIGBN6xmTA/2u62kM5k4ogmWmHZse8ZLimuBXaqCRL8/22\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">subset of the financing business</a>.</p>\n<p id=\"footnote-2\">[2] Disclosure: I used to work at Goldman, in an ECM derivatives business as it happens.</p>\n<p id=\"footnote-3\">[3] SpaceX and Alphabet presumably count in the second-quarter investment bank revenue numbers; SK Hynix and (obviously) Samsung do not.</p>\n<p id=\"footnote-4\">[4] Or, of course, sell some of the stocks they have now, but I guess the thesis of all of this is that there is more positive-expected-value equity financing to be done, so the investors should want to own more of it.</p>\n<p id=\"footnote-5\">[5] Adam Josephson of Sakonnet Research <a href=\"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/s/c/aNToGa3vx4yN4mYmdAw-wcVYXWvKEbg3fMCOPtwjWFWyJTTRdTnpiDZCTCgd4yprvnDG5I7ZI1zvYv379AzJ4i7v4zwPqp46pKwGRbeH4Ifj2_iDgXztr1BTOSZ-t1xsgqFApekV_GMqmYeZR5wU9tC-06UpoNP686-VqUk04RgnH93LGyKFOtXCNKdpj2pCXflsRr6yNTe_i_nLD9-8PkNjCzCA_qYBxvshk3WFL5c4wKXspmAWHoz4GpUAASup63K5vvlN7nORApZ2jarsKWu5Kroq3JoyPNCSllMzcEkS3GEqodq32bgzn3KzszWU4K99TUICAMlwNS5znwtdwDFye_lLQnsJWBaJIVhwG_6Jcm1R6yMR6yKqoAQ/aeVquoZw184ilvW4Ysxv9tre_AULubRG/22\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">wrote last month</a>: “For those wondering where all the retail and institutional money came from/is coming from to fund the SpaceX IPO and subsequent dramatic advance in its share price (myself included!), we got one likely answer today in the form of the latest margin debt data. … As margin debt continues to rise, so too does the S&amp;P 500, not the least bit surprisingly; one directly affects the other. Other levels of financial leverage are similarly historically high, including repurchase agreement (repo) lending and hedge fund borrowing.”</p>\n<p id=\"footnote-6\">[6] A two-step process of, like, “pay $100 today, borrow $70, put up $30 of equity, and then in a year do a dividend recap where you borrow another $30 and pay out a dividend to yourself” is not unheard-of, but that normally requires some valuation growth.</p>",
